elements.content: Deep-blue solutions of Y2+ formed from Y(NR2)3 (R = SiMe3) and excess potassium in the presence of 18-crown-6 at −45 °C under vacuum in diethyl ether react with CO at −78 °C to form colorless crystals of the (CO)1– radical complex, {[(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 1. The polymeric structure contains trigonal bipyramidal [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2– units with axial (CO)1– ligands linked by [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ dications. Byproducts such as the ynediolate, [(R2N)3Y]2(μ-OCCO){[K(18-crown-6)]2(18-crown-6)}, 2, in which two (CO)1– anions are coupled to form (OCCO)2–, and the insertion/rearrangement product, {(R2N)2Y[OC(CH2)Si(Me2)NSiMe3]}[K(18-crown-6)], 3, are common in these reactions that give variable results depending on the specific reaction conditions. The CO reduction in the presence of THF forms a solvated variant of 2, the ynediolate [(R2N)3Y]2(μ-OCCO)[K(18-crown-6)(THF)2]2, 2a. CO2 reacts analogously with Y2+ to form the (CO2)1– radical complex, {[(R2N)3Y(μ-CO2)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 4, that has a structure similar to that of 1. Analogous (CO)1– and (OCCO)2– complexes of lutetium were isolated using Lu(NR2)3/K/18-crown-6: {[(R2N)3Lu(μ-CO)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 5, [(R2N)3Lu]2(μ-OCCO){[K(18-crown-6)]2(18-crown-6)}, 6, and [(R2N)3Lu]2(μ-OCCO)[K(18-crown-6)(Et2O)2]2, 6a.

elements.content: Dinitrogen can be reduced to (N2)2– and (N2)3– via the combination of a trivalent rare earth salt and an alkali metal as shown in eq (Ln = rare earth, i.e., Sc, Y, lanthanides; A = anions such as amides, aryloxides, and cyclopentadienides; M = Na, K). Although the details of the dinitrogen reduction are not known for all the metals, in the case of yttrium, EPR evidence for an Y2+ species that reduces dinitrogen has been obtained. We describe here the first studies of the reactivity of the deep-blue solutions of Y2+ obtained from Y(NR2)3/K reactions (R = SiMe3) with substrates other than dinitrogen. Specifically, the reduction of CO to the (CO)1– radical and CO2 to the (CO2)1– radical are presented. The utility of the cyclic polyether, 18-crown-6, in isolating these radicals in surprisingly simple coordination complexes is described, as well as the formation of the dimer of the (CO)1– radical, i.e. (OCCO)2–. Analogous CO chemistry with lutetium is also included.

Although the details of the dinitrogen reduction are not known for all the metals, in the case of yttrium, EPR evidence for an Y2+ species that reduces dinitrogen has been obtained.  1  We describe here the first studies of the reactivity of the deep-blue solutions of Y2+ obtained from Y(NR2)3/K reactions (R = SiMe3) with substrates other than dinitrogen. Specifically, the reduction of CO to the (CO)1- radical and CO2 to the (CO2)1- radical are presented. The utility of the cyclic polyether, 18-crown-6, in isolating these radicals in surprisingly simple coordination complexes is described, as well as the formation of the dimer of the (CO)1- radical, i.e. (OCCO)2-. Analogous CO chemistry with lutetium is also included.

elements.content: Although CO reduction by potassium has been reported since 1825, complexes of the (CO)1– and (CO2)1– radicals are rare and have only previously been reported using the carefully designed tris(aryloxide) tacn ligands with uranium. Uranium complexes have also provided an extensive series of CO reduction products, namely the [(CO) n ]2– complexes in which n = 2–4. With lanthanides, n = 3 examples are known.

elements.content: CO reduction by Y2+ was accomplished in the following way. A deep-blue solution of Y2+ was generated at −45 °C from Y(NR2)3 and excess potassium mirror in diethyl ether under vacuum in the presence of 1 equiv of 18-crown-6. The mixture was filtered from the excess potassium and frozen with liquid nitrogen, and CO was added. After 15 min at −78 °C, the solution was orange. Colorless crystals of polymeric {[(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 1, Scheme , formed over 2 days at room temperature. The complex, identified by X-ray diffraction, Figure , has one Y(NR2)3 moiety coordinated on each side by (CO)K(18-c-6) units. Hence, formation of one monomeric repeat unit of 1 formally requires 2 equiv of Y2+, arising from two Y(NR2)3/K reactions, to reduce two molecules of CO leaving 1 equiv of Y(NR2)3 as the stoichiometric byproduct. Y(NR2)3 is observed in the crude product mixture, but quantification is complicated since some could be unreacted starting material.

elements.content: The reaction of CO with the deep-blue solutions formed from Y(NR2)3/K is highly sensitive to the form of potassium, the amount of 18-crown-6, the type of ether solvent, and reaction times and temperatures. At least 50 small variations of these parameters have been explored in order to optimize the results presented here. The Y(NR2)3/K/CO reaction is complicated by the fact that at least two byproducts are sometimes formed in this reaction, the ynediolate, [(R2N)3Y]2(μ-OCCO){[K(18-crown-6)]2(18-crown-6)}, 2, which was also identified by X-ray crystallography, Figure , and the CO insertion/rearrangement product, {(R2N)2Y[OC(CH2)Si(Me2)NSiMe3]}[K(18-crown-6)], 3, . Detailed characterization of 1 has been challenging since crystals of 1 do not redissolve in Et2O and reactions to synthesize 1 when exposed to THF give [(R2N)3Y]2(μ-OCCO)[K(18-crown-6)(THF)2]2, 2a, Scheme , , a variant of 2 that differs in its countercation. Complex 2a also forms when the Y(NR2)3/K reaction occurs in 1:1 THF/DME.

elements.content: The ynediolate complexes, 2 and 2a, contain the (OCCO)2– dianion formally derived by dimerization of two (CO)1– radicals. These complexes are very similar to the U4+ complex, (R2N)3U(μ-OCCO)U(NR2)3 (R = SiMe3), reported while this research was in progress by Arnold et al. as well as that of [U(C8H6{Si i Pr3-1,4}2)(C5Me5)]2(μ-OCCO). Complex 3 is likely to arise initially from insertion of CO into the Y–C bond of the metalated complex, (R2N)2Y[CH2Si(Me2)NSiMe3]K, known to form from Y(NR2)3 and K. Rearrangement of such acyls to enolates is common and would explain the observed structure of 3 (structural details in the (SI)).

elements.content: Complex 1 displays an IR absorption at 2091 cm–1 that is very close to the 2092 cm–1 value observed for the mixed valence U3+/U4+ complex [(L)U]2(μ-CO) (L = 1,4,7-tris(3,5-di-tert-butyl-2-hydroxybenzylate)-1,4,7-triazacyclononane). The IR spectrum of analogous crystals of 1 synthesized with 13CO lacks this absorption and has a band at 2048 cm–1 (calcd, 2043 cm–1), . The 13C{1H} NMR spectrum of the (O13C13CO)2– complex, 2a- 13 CO, exhibits a multiplet in the alkyne region at 55.5 ppm that matches an AA′XX′ simulation, which uses the coupling constants found for 2a: 2 J YC = 10.4 Hz and 3 J YC = 1.7 Hz, .

elements.content: In 1, the yttrium atom in the [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2– unit has a trigonal bipyramidal geometry with (CO)1– anions in the axial sites. Each potassium ion has a distorted hexagonal bipyramidal coordination environment with one crown ether providing six oxygen donor atoms situated above and below the equatorial plane, a carbonyl monoanion in one axial position, and an oxygen of the second crown ether in the other axial position. The dicationic [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ unit that connects the [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2– dianions into a polymer has two of these axial K–O(other crown) linkages, and their 2.996(2) and 3.032(2) Å K–O distances are longer than the other 14 K–O distances that range from 2.650(2) to 2.946(3) Å. The [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ unit that comprises a link in polymeric 1 has previously been observed in salts of (Ph3SiO)1–, [Ti(CO)4(μ-OC6H5)]2 2–, {[Sc(NCS)6]Cl}4–, (HgSe8)2–, and [Er(NCS)6(SCN)]4‑, but not in this polymeric form. Neither spectroscopic nor X-ray data (see for details) can distinguish Y–C–O–K from Y–O–C–K connectivity in 1. The Y–C–O–K assignment used in the equations and figures follows the relative Pauling electronegativities of Y (1.22) and K (0.82).
elements.clean_text: In 1, the yttrium atom in the [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2- unit has a trigonal bipyramidal geometry with (CO)1- anions in the axial sites. Each potassium ion has a distorted hexagonal bipyramidal coordination environment with one crown ether providing six oxygen donor atoms situated above and below the equatorial plane, a carbonyl monoanion in one axial position, and an oxygen of the second crown ether in the other axial position. The dicationic [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ unit that connects the [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2- dianions into a polymer has two of these axial K-O(other crown) linkages, and their 2.996(2) and 3.032(2) Å K-O distances are longer than the other 14 K-O distances that range from 2.650(2) to 2.946(3) Å. The [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ unit that comprises a link in polymeric 1 has previously been observed in salts of (Ph3SiO)1-, [Ti(CO)4(μ-OC6H5)]2 2-, {[Sc(NCS)6]Cl}4-, (HgSe8)2-, and [Er(NCS)6(SCN)]4-, but not in this polymeric form. Neither spectroscopic nor X-ray data (see  for details) can distinguish Y-C-O-K from Y-O-C-K connectivity in 1. The Y-C-O-K assignment used in the equations and figures follows the relative Pauling electronegativities of Y (1.22) and K (0.82).

elements.content: The ynediolate complexes 2 and 2a differ from 1 in that they are not polymeric even though 2 and 2a, like 1, contain dianionic components that are charge balanced by two [K(18-crown-6)]1+ cations. The difference presumably arises because the anionic charge from two (CO)1– ions sandwiches a neutral Y(NR2)3 unit in 1, whereas the anionic charge of the (OCCO)2– dianion is sandwiched inside of two neutral Y(NR2)3 moieties in 2 and 2a. Complex 2a has hexagonal bipyramidal potassium like 1, but the axial positions are occupied by THF of solvation and hence the bridging [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ connecting unit in 1 is not formed. Complex 2, which lacks the THF of solvation in 2a, adopts yet another mode of combining two [K(18-crown-6)]1+ cations with a third crown ether bridging the two cations as a bidentate ligand to each potassium to form a [K2(18-crown-6)3]2+ dication.

elements.content: The deep-blue Y2+ solutions generated as described above also react with CO2 and surprisingly make complexes of similar overall structure. In this case, a deep-blue Y2+ solution prepared at −45 °C as described above was cooled to −78 °C and exposed to 1 equiv of CO2 which led to an immediate color change to colorless. After workup, crystals of the (CO2)1– complex, {[(R2N)3Y(μ-CO2)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 4, Scheme , Figure , were isolated. Complex 4 is polymeric like 1 except that the ligand in between the yttrium and potassium centers is now the (CO2)1– radical anion instead of the (CO)1– radical. Again, [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ units link components in the extended polymer. The (CO2)1– anions are nearly linear with 179.1(4)° and 179.2(4)° O–C–O angles similar to the 178.0(3)° angle in the U4+ complex of the (CO2)1– radical anion, (L′)U(η1-OCO), L′ = 1,4,7-tris(3-adamantyl-5-tert-butyl-2-hydroxybenzylate)-1,4,7-triazacyclononane, previously reported by Meyer et al., which has an IR stretch of 2188 cm–1. The inequivalent 1.171(4)–1.198(4) Å C–O distances are more similar to each other than the disparate values in (L′)U(η1-OCO), 1.122(4) and 1.277(4) Å. The 2.352(3) and 2.367(3) Å Y–O distances are much longer than the 2.052(3)–2.057(1) Å analogs in 2 and 2a, which may be a reflection of the fact that the (OCO)1– ligand does not have a full negative charge per oxygen donor atom as in (OCCO)2–.

elements.content: A reaction analogous to Scheme was examined with lutetium. In this case, Lu(NR2)3 was treated with K in the presence of 18-crown-6 at −45 °C to give a deep-blue solution. This was frozen at −196 °C, CO at 1 atm was added, the reaction vessel was warmed to −78 °C, and the solution turned to orange yellow. Colorless crystals of an analog of 1, namely, {[(R2N)3Lu(μ-CO)2][K2(18-crown-6)2]} n , 5, were obtained at room temperature. Complex 5 was also characterized by X-ray crystallography, and although not isomorphous, it has a structure similar to that of 1, , . The lutetium reduction of CO readily forms an ynediolate complex analogous to the byproduct of the yttrium reaction. In the lutetium case, [(R2N)3Lu]2(μ-OCCO){[K(18-crown-6)]2(18-crown-6)}, 6 (), an analog of 2, can be crystallized as well as [(R2N)3Lu]2(μ-OCCO)[K(18-crown-6)(Et2O)2]2, 6a (), an analog of 2a except that two Et2O molecules solvate the potassium instead of two THF. The formation of 5, 6, and 6a suggests that the deep-blue solutions obtained from Lu(NR2)3 and potassium may contain Lu2+ in analogy to Y2+.

The formation of 5, 6, and 6a suggests that the deep-blue solutions obtained from Lu(NR2)3 and potassium may contain Lu2+ in analogy to Y2+.

elements.content: Density functional calculations described in detail in the were attempted on 1 even though semilocal density functionals suffer from various deficiencies for systems with strong noncovalent interactions. Calculations on [(R2N)3Y(μ-CO)2]2– did not give good agreement with the structure, but also did not include the interaction of the (CO)1– with potassium. Calculations were then attempted on the entire 172 atom {(R2N)3Y[(μ-CO)K(18-crown-6)]2} repeat unit. These also did not give good agreement, but again the full extent of interaction could not be calculated since the interactions between the two [K(18-crown-6)]1+ units in the polymer were not included. The calculations in each case showed very similar energies for triplet, singlet, and closed shell structures as well as structures with Y–O–C–K and Y–C–O–K connectivity.

elements.content: Although a detailed bonding picture is not available for these compounds, it is clear that the Y(NR2)3/K reduction system that generates Y2+ can be used to reduce CO and CO2 and trap these small molecules in crystallizable complexes as the (CO)1– and (CO2)1– radical anions. Although this first step in CO and CO2 reduction has previously been demonstrated with tris(aryloxide) tacn uranium complexes, this required the use of a carefully constructed tripodal coordination cavity. The isolation of 1 and 4 shows that these radical anions can be accessed in the more open coordination environments of a simple tris(amide) like Y(NR2)3; the isolation of 5 shows that this is extendable to the lanthanide series. It is likely that these (CO)1– and (CO2)1– radicals could be isolated because they formed an extended polymer of low solubility. The polymeric nature of the product was due in part to the linking ability of the [K(18-crown-6)]1+ cations to form bridging [K2(18-crown-6)2]2+ moieties. Hence, the use of 18-crown-6 is likely to be a crucial factor in generating these results.

elements.content: The dimerization of (CO)1– radicals to (OCCO)2– is not unexpected, but in the past this radical has only been postulated in reactions that reductively couple CO. Both lanthanide and actinide complexes can reductively homologate CO to [(CO) n ]2– ions where n = 2–4, but isolating (CO)1– and (OCCO)2– in the same reduction system has not been possible until now. The variable nature of the yields and product mixtures as a function of detailed reaction conditions attests to the high reactivity of these species.
